pmc Sci Rep Sci Rep 1579 scirep Scientific Reports 2045-2322 Nature Publishing Group PMC12485149 PMC12485149.1 12485149 12485149 41028445 10.1038/s41598-025-99260-w 99260 1 Article Integrated zooplankton and heavy metal analysis as indicators of pollution threats in freshwater ecosystems of West Bengal Islam Sk Saruk 1 Das Tilak 2 Shit Pravat Kumar 3 Midya Sujoy sujoy.midya@gmail.com 1 2 1 https://ror.org/027jsza11 grid.412834.8 0000 0000 9152 1805 Research Centre of Natural and Applied Sciences, Raja N. L. Khan Women’s College (Autonomous), Vidyasagar University, 2 3 30 9 2025 2025 15 478255 33779 19 9 2024 18 4 2025 30 09 2025 02 10 2025 02 10 2025 © The Author(s) 2025 2025 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Freshwater bodies are a vital resource for humans, yet they are threatened by numerous factors, many of which remain unidentified. In this study, we assessed the concentrations of seven heavy metals (HMs) in forty-eight water samples and analyzed their correlation with zooplankton populations and human health risks at four sub-divisional sites in West Bengal, India. Sampling was conducted throughout the year. We used indices based on HMs and zooplankton to evaluate human health risks. The results revealed that the total taxonomic richness of zooplankton (Rotifera, Copepoda, and Branchiopods) was 72 species, with Rotifera richness 25, Copepoda 37, and Branchiopods 10 species. These results demonstrated a negative correlation between zooplankton abundance and HMs concentration, highlighting zooplankton’s potential as significant indicator species. Pearson’s correlation analysis revealed a significant relationship between HMs concentration and zooplankton abundance ( P Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1038/s41598-025-99260-w. Keywords Ecological assessment Human health risk Metal pollution impact Pearson’s correlation coefficient Zooplankton distribution Subject terms Ecology Environmental sciences pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © Springer Nature Limited 2025 Introduction Zooplankton population placed as a key component in aquatic ecosystems and played a crucial role in food webs, diet requirement of micro and macro benthos, and transfer of energy to upper trophic levels 1 1 2 3 3 4 5 2 6 Aquatic ecosystems provide numerous essential functions for humans, but they have experienced significant changes in water conditions over the past few decades. These changes are largely driven by human activities and climate changes 1 7 8 9 10 11 12 13 14 Heavy metal toxicity is persistent and poses long-term risks to living organisms. Tchounwou et al. 15 16 17 18 19 20 20 21 22 23 24 25 As far as the literature is concerned, the impact of heavy metals on water quality in relation to the ecological status of zooplankton and human health risk assessment has not been thoroughly studied. In this research, we examine both heavy metal and zooplankton-based indices to determine the water quality and assess the human health risks associated with freshwater ecosystems. The study encompasses diverse environmental condition, including ponds, canals, and waterlogged areas, reflecting the various ways these water resources are utilized by different user groups. This approach allows for a more accurate and precise evaluation of potential risks or threats. Materials and methods Description of study area In India, 740 million rural people depend on freshwater sources, and about 38 million suffer from waterborne diseases 26 27 28 The present study investigates the East Medinipur district in West Bengal, which spans an area of 4713 square kilometers and is geographically located between 21°38′ and 22°31′ N latitude and 87°27′ and 88°12′ E longitude. According to the 2011 Census, the district has a population of 5.09 million people, with approximately 87% residing in urban areas and 13% in rural areas. The land use in this region is categorized into six main types based on satellite imagery: agriculture (46.41%), vegetation cover (33.06%), wetlands (12.27%), built-up areas (5.05%), water bodies (3%), and sandy tracts (0.20%). Local residents rely heavily on surface water bodies for their daily needs. Our survey found that among the 3% of land covered by water bodies, 67% of the population uses ponds for household purposes, 13% use canals, and 7% depend on waterlogged areas. It was observed that more than 60% of the population is affected by waterborne and skin diseases due to the regular use of these water resources. Consequently, medical expenses have increased by 30% of total household expenditure. For our study, we selected four sites within the district, each located in one of the four sub-divisional areas: Study Site-I (SI) in Tamluk (1084.30 sq. km), Study Site-II (SII) in Haldia (683.94 sq. km), Study Site-III (SIII) in Egra (940.96 sq. km), and Study Site-IV (SIV) in Contai (1251.21 sq. km). The district is rich in rivers, including the Rupnarayan (drainage area 5.23 sq. km), Haldi (5.21 sq. km), Rasulpur (4.71 sq. km), Kangsabati (2.69 sq. km), and Keleghai (1.62 sq. km), as well as canals and other water resources (Fig. 1 2  Fig. 1 Study area map of present investigation. The figure was generated using QGIS software (version 3.34.11) (URL: https://www.qgis.org  Fig. 2 Field survey and sample collection from different aquatic ecosystems during the investigation time. Sample collection and data processing We collected 48 samples from different water bodies such as, including pond ecosystems, canals, and waterlogged areas. Each site was further divided into four sub-sampling locations. Zooplankton were collected using both WP2 plankton net with a 50 cm diameter and 200 μm mesh size, and Nylobolt plankton net (52 μm) for specially microzooplankton 29 30 31 32 33 30 Heavy metals (HMs) analysis of the water samples A total of 48 samples were collected from a depth of 0.5 m within a 5-meter radius of the designated sampling points 23 3 To analyze heavy metal (HM) concentrations, the samples were acid digested using a concentrated solution of HNO 3 4 3 34 Data analysis Dominant species Dominant species within the study area were identified using dominance index (Y) 35 1 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
