ul numerical method used to identify differences and similarities between multiple variables. Researchers frequently use this technique to analyze water quality parameters 7 49 50 5  Fig. 5 Dendrogram of hierarchical cluster analysis of ( a b c d Discussion In the 21st century, over population, direct discharge of contaminant, and anthropogenic pollution are the key problems in the global scenario, which reflected the crucial effect on aquatic health as well as the ecosystems 7 23 51 52 This aspect of the study is critical, as the HPI index showed a substantial increase in pollution levels. During the observation period, about 64.58% of water samples shifted from moderately polluted to heavily polluted, and approximately 18.75% became heavily polluted (Table 1 48 1 53 54 As per the result of Hierarchical Cluster Analysis (HCA), it suggests that occurrence of zooplankton and seven different heavy metals in the same water bodies. The HMs likely enter aquatic systems from common sources such as industrial waste, agricultural runoff, and municipal waste. This clustering suggests potential ecological interactions between the heavy metals and zooplankton community structure. Non-carcinogenic health risk assessments for the seven heavy metals revealed that nickel (Ni) and zinc (Zn) pose the highest potential health risks for both children and adults at all study sites (Table 2 55 7 52 7 52 Given the observed decline in zooplankton populations and rising heavy metal pollution, there is an urgent need for scientific management practices to protect water quality and human health. Although the HI analysis for dermal contact showed no immediate risks, cost-effective remediation techniques should be implemented to improve water quality. Further research is also needed to explore the relationship between zooplankton abundance, health hazard indices for heavy metals, and GIS-based studies to better understand the situation. Effective solutions are essential, as these aquatic systems provide critical ecosystem services. It is crucial for industrial sectors, agricultural bodies, and other stakeholders to comply with environmental standards and regulations to prevent contamination. Municipalities should establish designated areas for domestic waste disposal, and urban authorities should encourage the use of personal reverse osmosis (RO) purification systems. Additionally, the use of chemical fertilizers and pesticides should be regulated. Public awareness campaigns at the village level can also help reduce pollution in aquatic ecosystems. Conclusion Freshwater ecosystems are vital for human health but are often threatened by unrecognized dangers. This study assessed the concentrations of seven HMs in 48 water samples and their impact on zooplankton populations and human health risks across four sub-divisional sites in West Bengal, India. The research was conducted seasonally throughout the year, utilizing indices based on HMs and zooplankton to evaluate health risks. The results indicated annual average zooplankton richness of 1063.5 individuals per liter (ind./L) in ponds, 850.56 ind./L in canals, and 973.44 ind./L in water-logged systems. Rotifers were found at densities of 402.06 ind./L, 334.88 ind./L, and 377.06 ind./L, respectively; copepods at 390.38 ind./L, 288.13 ind./L, and 346.19 ind./L; and branchiopods at 271.06 ind./L, 227.56 ind./L, and 250.19 ind./L, respectively. A negative correlation between zooplankton abundance and HMs concentrations suggests that zooplankton could serve as effective pollution indicators. Pearson’s correlation coefficient and hierarchical cluster analysis confirmed a significant relationship between HMs and zooplankton ( P The Metal Index and Nemerow Pollution Index showed that 83.34% and 97.92% of water samples, respectively, were contaminated by HMs. Nickel (Ni) and Zinc (Zn) were identified as metals with the highest health risk potential. The Health Hazard Index (HI) values revealed that children are at higher risk (HI > 1), mainly through ingestion, while adults face greater risks from dermal exposure. These findings provide crucial baseline data, underscoring the urgent need for measures to mitigate environmental health risks and promote sustainable practices. Electronic supplementary material Below is the link to the electronic supplementary material.  Supplementary Material 1. Publisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements Acknowledgments: The authors show their kind acknowledgment to the Dept. of Zoology, Raja N. L. Khan Women’s College (Autonomous) affiliated with Vidyasagar University, Midnapore, West Bengal, India for the laboratory facilities and kind encouragement. Author contributions S.S.I.: Writing—review & editing, Conceptualization, Methodology, Data curation, Validation, Formal analysis, Software, Writing—original draft. T.D.: Writing—original draft, Formal analysis, Data curation. P.K.S.: Writing—review & editing, Methodology. S.M.: Conceptualization, Writing—original draft, Writing—review & editing, Validation, Supervision. All authors have read and approved the final manuscript. Data availability The datasets used and analysed during the current study are available from the corresponding author on reasonable request. Declarations Competing interests The authors declare no competing interests. Consent for publication The authors affirm that human research participants provided informed consent, for publication of the images in Fig. 2 5. References 1. Aubakirova M The current state of zooplankton diversity in the middle Caspian sea during spring Diversity 2023 15 7 798 10.3390/d15070798 Aubakirova, M. et al. The current state of zooplankton diversity in the middle Caspian sea during spring. Diversity 15 2. Toklu-Alicli B Balkis-Ozdelice N Durmus T Balci M Relationship between environmental factors and zooplankton diversity in the Gulf of Bandir